DESCRIPTION:Last class we created code to read and write to SPI based SRAM.
   This time we will be using parallel SRAM.\nAgenda:\n     1. Difference be
 tween SPI and parallel interfaces\n     2. Look over the datasheet\n     3.
  Wire up all required pins\n     4. Write code to write to\, and read from 
 the SRAM\n     5. Convert the read and write code to functions\nIf you cann
 ot attend the class in person\, E-Mail arduino@unallocatedspace.org and ask
  to be added to the Google Hangout. The hangout will generally be started j
 ust before class (6:45-7:15 PM). If you do not have an invite by 7:15\, ple
 ase E-Mail arduino@unallocatedspace.org.\nThe slides for the upcoming and p
 revious classes can be found at https://drive.google.com/folderview?id=0Bzp
 bYvv0G2kMTURwUVhhMWFXX0k&usp=sharing.  The slides are generally made during
  the three days before a class.\nRequired Items:\n     1. An Arduino board 
 of some kind (Uno\, Due\, Mega\, Boarduino\, Duemilanove\, etc)\n     2. If
  your board does not have USB programming built in\, you will need a progra
 mmer (AVRISP\, Bus Pirate\, Bus Blaster\, AVR Dragon\, another Arduino\, et
 c)\n     3. Breadboard (the long one if possible\, though the small square-
 ish ones are okay for now)\n     4. USB cable for your board and/or program
 mer\n     5. Laptop with the Arduino IDE installed (Linux\, Windows\, or Ma
 c)\n     6. Jumper wires for your breadboard\nProvided Items:\n     1. SRAM
  chip (AS6C62256 - http://www.alliancememory.com/pdf/AS6C62256.pdf)\n     \
 nSince Unallocated Space runs off of donations\, we would like to mention t
 hat the recommended donation for this class is $5. It is by no means a requ
 irement\, but it does help us keep the lights on!  Attendance to the space\
 , and this class\, is 100% free to all!\n
LAST-MODIFIED:20171216T232911Z
LOCATION:Unallocated Space\, 512 Shaw Court #105\, Severn\, MD 21144\, Unit
 ed States
