BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20141205T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20141205T220000
DTSTAMP:20250626T025311Z
UID:r6utgh0vigic1fthu1bcjpgo9g@google.com
RECURRENCE-ID;TZID=America/New_York:20141205T190000
CREATED:20171216T230211Z
DESCRIPTION:Having finished the seven segment projects\, it's time to move 
 on to something a little more demanding.  We will take a look at serial com
 munications with the Arduino.  We will go over what serial actually is\, an
 d how it is sent.  Then we will dig into actually communicating between the
  laptop and Arduino by having the Arduino simply echo back whatever it gets
 .  After that we will change the design so that the data sent from the lapt
 op will change the brightness of an LED.  If time permits\, we will go over
  SoftwareSerial and use it to connect two Arduino's together.\n\nAgenda:\n 
     1. What is serial\n     2. 8N1 encoding\n     3. UARTs\n     4. Using t
 he serial library\n     5. Create sketch to talk to the Arduino over serial
 \n     6. Set LED brightness with serial\n     7. Time permitting:\n       
    a. SoftwareSerial\n          b. Connect to another Arduino with Software
 Serial\n\n     \nIf you cannot attend the class in person\, E-Mail arduino@
 unallocatedspace.org and ask to be added to the Google Hangout.  The hangou
 t will generally be started just before class (6:45-7:15 PM).  If you do no
 t have an invite by 7:15\, please E-Mail arduino@unallocatedspace.org.\n\nT
 he slides for the upcoming and previous classes can be found at https://dri
 ve.google.com/folderview?id=0BzpbYvv0G2kMTURwUVhhMWFXX0k&usp=sharing.  The 
 slides are generally made during the three days before a class.\n\nRequired
  Items:\n     1. An Arduino board of some kind (Uno\, Due\, Mega\, Boarduin
 o\, Duemilanove\, etc)\n     2. If your board does not have USB programming
  built in\, you will need a programmer (AVRISP\, Bus Pirate\, Bus Blaster\,
  AVR Dragon\, another Arduino\, etc)\n     3. Breadboard (the long one if p
 ossible\, though the small square-ish ones are okay for now)\n     4. USB c
 able for your board and/or programmer\n     5. Laptop with the Arduino IDE 
 installed (Linux\, Windows\, or Mac)\n     6. Jumper wires for your breadbo
 ard\n\nProvided Items:\n     1. Breadboard and jumpers (if you don't have a
 ny of either)\n     2. LEDs\n     3. Resistors (200-1\,000 Ohm)\n\nSince Un
 allocated Space runs off of donations\, we would like to mention that the r
 ecommended donation for this class is $5. It is by no means a requirement\,
  but it does help us keep the lights on!  Attendance to the space\, and thi
 s class\, is 100% free to all!
LAST-MODIFIED:20171216T232911Z
LOCATION:Unallocated Space\, 512 Shaw Ct #105\, Severn\, MD\, United States
SEQUENCE:0
STATUS:CONFIRMED
SUMMARY:Arduino Night
TRANSP:OPAQUE
