UID:t5bmdsjg9u7mhhmff5lg8kc434@google.com
CREATED:20171216T230211Z
DESCRIPTION:Do you have an interest in Morse Code?   Would you like to see 
 how it's possible to send intelligent radio signals for hundreds of miles w
 ith just milliwatts of power?\n\nCome out for CW/QRP night!\n\nOur first me
 eting will be on Tuesday night 7/5/16 from 7 to 10pm.\n\nThis first meeting
  will be to discuss what people are looking to get out of this and to provi
 de some tips on learning Morse Code\, the fundamental mode of communication
 s for QRP or low power communications.  We'll also give you some tips on ho
 w you can use today's tech to decode this and see what everyone is talking 
 about without even knowing Morse Code!\nEveryone who attends will receive a
  Morse Code cheat sheet with each of the letters and some of the special Q 
 codes commonly used in CW communications.\n\nEven If your not sure if you'd
  be interested in this\, come on out anyway to learn about this popular par
 t of the Amateur Radio hobby.\n\n73's and 88's!
LAST-MODIFIED:20171216T232911Z
SEQUENCE:1
STATUS:CONFIRMED
SUMMARY:CW/QRP Night
TRANSP:OPAQUE
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20140201T220000Z
DTEND:20140202T020000Z
DTSTAMP:20250626T025311Z
UID:t88bi7b862f9qtnc75sgf1a7lk@google.com
CREATED:20171216T230211Z
DESCRIPTION:Want to build your own OS? Learn how things work at a lower lev
 el? Dust off or build up some assembly skills? Get into that nitty gritty C
 ? Then this class is for you! Suggested skillset: \nPrior programming exper
 ience in procedural languages \nThe ability to read and parse C (writing no
 t required\, we'll get into that) \nPrior familiarization with assembly\, t
 he ability to code in assembly is NOT required\, that will be taught along 
 the way. \nKnowledge of common compilers\, linkers\, and assemblers \nHEX a
 nd Binary understanding \nRudimentary LINUX/UNIX experience (for explaining
  concepts) \nBasic knowledge of usage of virtualization tools such as BOCHS
 \, VirtualBox\, QEMU\, VMware workstation\, etc. "Low level programming is 
 fun and exciting!" Starting from where the BIOS leaves us to jumping into 6
 4-bit LONG mode on x86_64 (amd64/EMT64 as the manufactures like to call the
 m!) processors\, we'll start at the beginning and build upwards! Knock down
  and explore topics that look daunting\, but can be broken down into simple
  blocks: Interrupts (Hardware vs Software) \nCPU Modes \nBootloaders \nKern
 els \nScheduling \nMemory Management \nFile Systems \nUser Interfaces (CLI 
 to start with...) \nApplication Execution \nAnd other great things! Date an
 d time to be determined\, mainly\, on the group's idea of what time and day
  would work the best and available scheduled times. Individual segments for
  the main class after fundamentals are covered\, will be part lecture\, par
 t development driven. This will be a long many session class covering all o
 f the topics\, they will be split into separate sections so you can attend 
 only the sections you wish to\, but there will be a class long project culm
 inating in a complete OS environment. I envision this taking a few months t
 o run through the basics and get a basic environment going. Moving on to ad
 vanced topics after we've got a functional system developed will be class c
 onsensus directed as to what we wish to do with the system\, and what featu
 res we want to add. This will be a seperate group of classes to be organize
 d when we have ideas about what to pursue as a group afterwards.
LAST-MODIFIED:20171216T232911Z
LOCATION:Unallocated Space\, 512 Shaw Court #105\, Severn\, MD\, United Sta
 tes
SEQUENCE:0
STATUS:CONFIRMED
SUMMARY:First OS Dev class
TRANSP:OPAQUE
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
