DESCRIPTION:SUMMARY: Do you like solving ciphers but want to grow beyond ro
 t13 puzzles? Are you interested in steamy romances involving Alice\, Bob\, 
 and Eve? Do you want to learn how to crack one time pads? Do you want to kn
 ow how you're using SSL wrong? Or maybe you're doing SSL right\, but you ke
 ep hearing about this BEAST attack and want to understand it on a cryptolog
 ist's level? Did you ever want to take the Stanford Online Crypto Course bu
 t feared the math?\n\nThen the Stanford Crypto 1 Study Group is the event o
 f the year for you! Together we will conquer the math and mystery of Crypto
 . Break down nerdy concepts into everyday concepts.\n\nThe Stanford Crypto 
 1 course is an online course provided by Coursera. The course begins with a
  detailed discussion of how two parties who have\na shared secret key can c
 ommunicate securely when a powerful adversary\neavesdrops and tampers with 
 traffic. The second half of\nthe course discusses public-key techniques tha
 t let two parties generate\na shared secret key. Throughout the course part
 icipants will be exposed\nto many exciting open problems in the field and w
 ork on fun\nprogramming projects.\n\nhttps://www.coursera.org/learn/crypto\
 n\nThe study sessions is for people to point out areas of the material that
  they didnt understand\, and for everyone else to come up with the best way
  to explain it. PLEASE DO NOT BE AFRAID TO SAY YOU DON'T KNOW SOMETHING. Th
 is is crypto\, we know its difficult\, that's why we find it alluring. Toge
 ther we'll be able to help each other. No judging\, No shame. #ELI5\n\nPyth
 on is language of choice\, but we'll try to accommodate others as best as p
 ossible\n\nTL\;DR: If you take this class\, you will be able to complete CT
 F Crypto challenges!\n\nGOAL: Complete the Stanford Crypto Course 1 like a 
 boss\n\nTHINGS TO BRING: Your development environment of choice\, and somet
 hing to take notes in\n\nSKILL LEVEL: Algebra is nice\, Calculus is great\,
  but not mandatory. Functional programming is highly suggested.\n\nPRESENTE
